   <abstract>The central thesis of the following dissertation is that we should understand moral worth as the practical corollary of knowledge. I therefore agree with those standard accounts of moral worth which maintain that moral worth requires us to perform right actions because they are right. I disagree however with how those accounts unpack the relevant notion of 'because.' I argue that just as believing something because it is true requires far more than an agent reasoning from the correct set of premises; so too performing an action because it is right requires far more than performing the action for the correct reasons. I argue that to understand the role that rightness plays in morally worthy action, we must look beyond the content of an agent's reasons and towards the underlying dispositions from which an agent acts. Such an approach, I go on to argue, allows us to resolve persistent puzzles surrounding both moral fetishism and moral testimony. Finally, in the most speculative part of the dissertation, I argue that we have similar reason to take a moral-worth-first approach to ethics that we do to take a knowledge-first approach to epistemology. Just as we cannot define knowledge in terms of analytic additions to true belief, so we won't be able to define moral worth in terms of analytic additions to right action. Yet, despite that, we can still give important and non-trivial characterizations of moral worth and employ the concept fruitfully in understanding other moral categories. Moral worth is, I argue, amongst the most fundamental ethical conceptsâ€”moral wort is the most general description of essentially rightive activity, and most other ethical concepts involve abstractions, approximations, generalizations, and deviations from it.</abstract>
